Satan is variously: the enemy, the adversary (Satan), the distant one (Shai'Tan), and the morningstar, the shining one (Lucifer). Amara is Death incarnate. While both are the negative voices in our head (Amara tempting Buddha, Satan tempting Christ), it is only Satan who is unredeemable.

While there is one Satan above all others, and who Christianity proscribes no redemption, no mercy, Mara is various beings, and one only has to be Mara for a time. He points out various incarnations of Mara who then become later incarnations of Buddha.

Instead of Satan being an other to be condemned, Mara is one of us, just as worthy of our compassion, and just as redeemable as any of us.
